WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.640
Well if you would please turn with me to the book of Exodus. We've been going through this book as a church family

2
00:00:04.640 --> 00:00:08.000
and we are nearing the end of our series.

3
00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:13.500
And we're going to be looking today in Exodus 33 and 34.

4
00:00:13.500 --> 00:00:16.200
Exodus 33 and 34.

5
00:00:16.200 --> 00:00:22.000
It's also there in your worship guide if you'd like to look there if you've not got a Bible with you.

6
00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:29.000
We'll begin reading in verse 18 with Moses' request here.

7
00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:34.000
Moses said, Please show me your glory.

8
00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:42.000
And he said, I will make all my goodness pass before you and will proclaim before you my name, the Lord.

9
00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:48.000
And I will be gracious to whom I will be gracious and I will show mercy on whom I will show mercy.

10
00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:57.000
But he said, You cannot see my face for man shall not see my face and live.

11
00:00:57.000 --> 00:01:02.000
The Lord said, Behold there is a place by me where you shall stand on the rock.

12
00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:10.000
And while my glory passes by I will put you in a cleft of the rock and I will cover you with my hand until I have passed by.

13
00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:17.000
Then I will take away my hand and you shall see my back but my face shall not be seen.

14
00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:22.000
The Lord said to Moses, Cut for yourselves two tablets of stone like the first.

15
00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:27.000
And I will write on the tablets the words that were on the first tablets which you broke.

16
00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:35.000
Be ready by the morning and come up in the morning to Mount Sinai and present yourself there to me on the top of the mountain.

17
00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:40.000
No one shall come up with you and let no one be seen throughout all the mountain.

18
00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:44.000
Let no flocks or herds graze opposite that mountain.

19
00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:48.000
So Moses cut two tablets of stone like the first.

20
00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:57.000
And he rose early in the morning and went up on Mount Sinai as the Lord had commanded him and took in his hands two tablets of stone.

21
00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:03.000
The Lord descended in the cloud and stood with him there and proclaimed the name of the Lord.

22
00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:11.000
The Lord passed before him and proclaimed, The Lord, the Lord, a God merciful and gracious,

23
00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:18.000
slow to anger and abounding in steadfast love and faithfulness, keeping steadfast love for thousands,

24
00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:25.000
forgiving iniquity and transgression and sin, but who will by no means clear the guilty,

25
00:02:25.000 --> 00:02:32.000
visiting the iniquity of the fathers on their children and the children's children to the third and fourth generation.

26
00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:37.000
And Moses quickly bowed his head toward the earth and worshiped.

27
00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:46.000
And he said, If now I have found favor in your sight, O Lord, please let the Lord go in the midst of us for it is a stiff-necked people

28
00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:52.000
and pardon our iniquity and our sin and take us for your inheritance.

29
00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:54.000
This is the word of the Lord.

30
00:02:54.000 --> 00:02:56.000
Let's pray.

31
00:02:56.000 --> 00:03:00.000
Well, we thank you so much for the gift of your word.

32
00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:07.000
We also thank you for the gift of your spirit who opens our eyes to see you in your word.

33
00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:11.000
And so Lord, I pray that you would open our eyes now to see more of Jesus.

34
00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:13.000
We pray this in his name.

35
00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:15.000
Amen.

36
00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:22.000
Well, on Valentine's Day, Julia and I went to go see a movie called Solo Mio.

37
00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:24.000
I don't know if anybody else saw that one.

38
00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:25.000
It was pretty good.

39
00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:35.000
The premise of the film is that there is this engaged couple who's booked a kind of two-for-one, all-inclusive wedding and honeymoon trip in Italy.

40
00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:39.000
So you go there and you kind of, you're there with a group and you have the wedding ceremony.

41
00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:44.000
And then after that, you've got all of these kind of couples' excursions all across Italy.

42
00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:47.000
But there is a problem.

43
00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:52.000
The bride to be decides not to go through with the wedding.

44
00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:57.000
And the husband to be is left standing there on the altar.

45
00:03:57.000 --> 00:04:00.000
So the groom faces this dilemma.

46
00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:02.000
What should he do about this trip?

47
00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:05.000
It was never meant to be alone.

48
00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:07.000
Does he go it solo or not?

49
00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:11.000
So it's a really kind of sad start to the movie.

50
00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:13.000
Well, this is the dilemma in some ways.

51
00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:16.000
We are coming across here in Exodus 33.

52
00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:20.000
But what we're reading here is far worse.

53
00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:30.000
God tells Moses, when you look at the start of chapter 33, that it's time to depart from Mount Sinai and for the people to make their way to the promised land.

54
00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:35.000
He tells them that an angel is going to go before them and is going to drive out their enemies.

55
00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:40.000
He tells them that the land that they are going to enter is a land full of abundance.

56
00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:43.000
It's a land flowing with milk and honey.

57
00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:47.000
But there is a problem.

58
00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:48.000
Here's the problem.

59
00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:52.000
God himself is not going to be going with them.

60
00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:55.000
The trip was going to have to be a solo trip.

61
00:04:55.000 --> 00:04:58.000
They'd have to go it alone.

62
00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:02.000
Now, God has good reasons to not go with them.

63
00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:05.000
They have been unfaithful to him.

64
00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:14.000
Only days after they made their covenant vows before the Lord, they forsook him and began to worship and idol instead.

65
00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:18.000
We saw that last week with the worshiping of the golden calf.

66
00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:26.000
But God's refusal to go with them wasn't him giving them what they deserved because of their idolatry.

67
00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:28.000
Rather, it was a mercy.

68
00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:31.000
He's actually withholding judgment.

69
00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:34.000
Here's what he says in chapter 33 verse 3.

70
00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:39.000
He says, I won't go up with you lest I consume you on the way.

71
00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:44.000
In other words, his holy presence would have meant their destruction.

72
00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:49.000
So by not going, he's actually withholding judgment from them.

73
00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:52.000
That's not how it felt.

74
00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:55.000
It feels like they're having to go it alone.

75
00:05:55.000 --> 00:05:57.000
This is devastating news.

76
00:05:57.000 --> 00:06:00.000
And the journey that they were on wasn't ultimately about the land.

77
00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:06.000
It was about, as we've seen time and time again, this is about their relationship with their redeemer.

78
00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:14.000
He saved them that they might know him, that they might walk in his ways and that they might be with him.

79
00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:16.000
Moses knew this.

80
00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:19.000
You know, Moses also knew that God had shown him favor.

81
00:06:19.000 --> 00:06:25.000
He knew that it was the Lord's grace, that he had made this people his own people.

82
00:06:25.000 --> 00:06:31.000
And so he prays, Moses comes before the Lord and prays that the Lord would remain with them.

83
00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:35.000
He would go with them on the way to the promised land.

84
00:06:35.000 --> 00:06:45.000
And so wonderfully, the Lord agrees to show them even more of the riches of his mercy and continue with them on the journey.

85
00:06:45.000 --> 00:06:47.000
But Moses doesn't finish there.

86
00:06:47.000 --> 00:06:52.000
God says, okay, I'll be with you and I'll show you mercy along the way.

87
00:06:52.000 --> 00:06:54.000
But Moses says, I want one more thing.

88
00:06:54.000 --> 00:06:57.000
And that's where we get to what we read just a moment ago.

89
00:06:57.000 --> 00:07:03.000
Moses prays, please show me your glory.

90
00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:08.000
That's where we're going to be focusing our attention this morning, this bold request.

91
00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:13.000
Yes, you're coming with us, but show me even more of your glory.

92
00:07:13.000 --> 00:07:22.000
And as we look at this, I want us to be reminded that we were created to know the Lord, to live in relationship with him, to be with him forever.

93
00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:28.000
And not only that, we were meant to see and savor his glory.

94
00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:36.000
The Lord saves us with that purpose in view that we might see and know him for who he truly is and be satisfied in him.

95
00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:41.000
So this morning we are being invited to join Moses in this prayer.

96
00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:46.000
To pray, Lord, please show me your glory.

97
00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:50.000
So what we're going to do is we're going to look at Moses' request and what it's all about.

98
00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:55.000
And we're going to see how God responds to that with all of us praying the same thing, hopefully.

99
00:07:55.000 --> 00:08:01.000
So let's look at this request. What do we learn from that request itself? Please show me your glory.

100
00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:05.000
First of all, it's a request for revelation.

101
00:08:05.000 --> 00:08:07.000
Show me your glory.

102
00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:13.000
So Moses is asking God to reveal something about himself, namely his glory.

103
00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:18.000
But what does that even mean? We keep saying this word glory. What are we talking about here?

104
00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:26.000
Well, glory, God's glory isn't like one of his attributes alongside all of his others.

105
00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:32.000
The Bible talks about God's glory. It's talking about the splendor of all that he is.

106
00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:37.000
It's the radiance of his manifold perfections.

107
00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:44.000
It is the stunning beauty of his very being.

108
00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:47.000
It's called glory.

109
00:08:47.000 --> 00:08:53.000
And the fact is we are hardwired to be drawn to things like that. We are attracted to glorious things.

110
00:08:53.000 --> 00:08:58.000
This is why we enjoy going to things like a concert or like a professional sporting event

111
00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:04.000
and seeing a team doing really well. We're drawn into that or going to a national park

112
00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:08.000
and seeing the grandeur of that. And this could go on.

113
00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:13.000
We have a hunger to see glory.

114
00:09:13.000 --> 00:09:20.000
But this here is pointing us to a far greater and all satisfying glory that we were made to know.

115
00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:24.000
I love how Paul David Tripp describes our desire to behold glory.

116
00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:27.000
It's almost been like a spiritual GPS that God has built into us.

117
00:09:27.000 --> 00:09:35.000
Like we want to see glory. And it's because God has built us into us so that we look ultimately to him.

118
00:09:35.000 --> 00:09:37.000
It points us to our Creator.

119
00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:41.000
So how can we see God's glory? It must be revealed.

120
00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:44.000
It's God's to show.

121
00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:51.000
You see, the glory of God isn't something that we merely like figure out with our own intellect by studying more.

122
00:09:51.000 --> 00:09:57.000
It's not something that we kind of just feel our way towards, you know, with our own like spiritual intuition

123
00:09:57.000 --> 00:10:02.000
or something along those lines. Rather, it's something that God gives.

124
00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:05.000
It's a gift from him revealing his glory.

125
00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:13.000
So Moses knew that it was God's initiative to come and make himself known to him, for example, at the burning bush.

126
00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:20.000
It was God's initiative to come down on Mount Sinai to make himself known and to give his word there.

127
00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:26.000
So it must be God who can reveal more of his glory to Moses.

128
00:10:26.000 --> 00:10:31.000
By the way, to say that it's God who does this isn't a call to passivity in this either.

129
00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:35.000
Note this. Moses is praying for this revelation.

130
00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:41.000
God invites us to seek after him and he calls us to seek after him.

131
00:10:41.000 --> 00:10:43.000
So Moses is praying, God show me your glory.

132
00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:47.000
And this is what we should be praying and seeking after as well.

133
00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:51.000
Because God is pleased to answer this prayer.

134
00:10:51.000 --> 00:10:54.000
So reveals who God is, his glory.

135
00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:58.000
But it's also revealing something about Moses, particularly his heart.

136
00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:00.000
Moses desires.

137
00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:03.000
So what is this telling us about Moses desires that this is what he prays?

138
00:11:03.000 --> 00:11:09.000
This, it's telling us this. That Moses desires God more than anything else.

139
00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:14.000
You see, the most important thing in his life is his relationship with God.

140
00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:17.000
So this is what he prays for. This is the top of his list.

141
00:11:17.000 --> 00:11:20.000
He wants the Lord himself.

142
00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:24.000
You know, when he was told that God would not be going with them to the promised land,

143
00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:31.000
Moses said this to him. He says, if your presence will not go with us, I don't want to go.

144
00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:39.000
So offer Moses a good life of overflowing abundance without the Lord.

145
00:11:39.000 --> 00:11:41.000
And he's not interested.

146
00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:50.000
He would far rather have the hardship and homelessness of the desert and know the Lord in the midst of it.

147
00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:54.000
He would rather know the Lord in hardship than a picture perfect life without the Lord.

148
00:11:54.000 --> 00:11:59.000
You see, Moses' desire, he knows that what he needs is in the Lord himself.

149
00:11:59.000 --> 00:12:05.000
And when God granted Moses requests to remain with them, Moses was no doubt delighted.

150
00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:09.000
But you know, he doesn't say, well, thank you very much. Looking forward to you being with us.

151
00:12:09.000 --> 00:12:12.000
He says, I want to know even more.

152
00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:14.000
So he knows the Lord.

153
00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:17.000
And the sign that he knows the Lord is he wants to know the Lord even more.

154
00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:21.000
This is an indication that someone has truly tasted and seen that the Lord is good.

155
00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:28.000
Because when you've tasted and seen that he is good, you thirst for more of him.

156
00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:31.000
Because his glory is greater than anything in the world.

157
00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:35.000
This is what the apostle Paul described when he said, I count, and this is Philippians 3.8.

158
00:12:35.000 --> 00:12:44.000
He said, I count everything is lost compared to the surpassing worth of knowing Christ Jesus my Lord.

159
00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:50.000
So the worth of Jesus is far surpassing anything else in this world.

160
00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:53.000
So let me just apply this personally.

161
00:12:53.000 --> 00:12:58.000
What has the gaze of your heart this morning?

162
00:12:58.000 --> 00:13:00.000
What is it that you are desiring?

163
00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:05.000
What's filling your mind and your affections?

164
00:13:05.000 --> 00:13:08.000
Let's bring it to exactly where we are this morning.

165
00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:12.000
One way to consider whether or not God himself is truly our heart's desire

166
00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:16.000
is to consider why we've come to church.

167
00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:18.000
Why are we here?

168
00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:20.000
People come to church for a lot of reasons.

169
00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:22.000
And good reasons.

170
00:13:22.000 --> 00:13:26.000
People think, as we've seen this morning, it's a good environment to raise their children in.

171
00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:31.000
There's a good way of life that's put before us.

172
00:13:31.000 --> 00:13:35.000
There are lots of benefits we could think of.

173
00:13:35.000 --> 00:13:37.000
We're stars for friendships.

174
00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:41.000
This is a good place to make friends.

175
00:13:41.000 --> 00:13:43.000
But the heart check that we all need is this.

176
00:13:43.000 --> 00:13:50.000
Are we here mostly because we want God's gifts or because we want God himself?

177
00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:51.000
Now don't get me wrong.

178
00:13:51.000 --> 00:13:53.000
We praise God for his gifts.

179
00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:54.000
We thank him for them.

180
00:13:54.000 --> 00:13:55.000
We seek after it.

181
00:13:55.000 --> 00:14:06.000
But above and beyond all of that, our supreme desire, the supreme desire of our hearts should be God in seeing his glory.

182
00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:14.000
The Lord working us in such a way that like Moses we would say, I'd rather live in the desert with the Lord than in paradise without him.

183
00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:23.000
One day the hymn writer, Fanny Crosby, heard a neighbor of hers complaining that he didn't have enough money to do what he was wanting to do.

184
00:14:23.000 --> 00:14:27.000
And here she was blind from infancy.

185
00:14:27.000 --> 00:14:32.000
And she couldn't do near the stuff that he could already do even without the money.

186
00:14:32.000 --> 00:14:39.000
But she started thinking about what she had in Jesus was far greater than anything in the world that she could have without him.

187
00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:42.000
So she started writing down this hymn.

188
00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:43.000
She wrote this.

189
00:14:43.000 --> 00:14:46.000
She wrote, Take the world but give me Jesus.

190
00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:50.000
Let me view his constant smile.

191
00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:54.000
Then throughout this life's long journey he will lead me all the while.

192
00:14:54.000 --> 00:14:57.000
Take the world but give me Jesus.

193
00:14:57.000 --> 00:15:05.000
In his cross my trust shall be till with clearer, brighter vision, face to face my Lord I see.

194
00:15:05.000 --> 00:15:11.000
That's what it sounds like for the Lord himself to have captivated someone's heart.

195
00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:15.000
This revelation of glory hopefully will lead us to pray the same thing.

196
00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:18.000
To ask the Lord to make himself known to us.

197
00:15:18.000 --> 00:15:23.000
To give us a greater desire for him and to fulfill that desire by showing us more of himself.

198
00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:26.000
Alright, so that's the request.

199
00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:30.000
Now secondly, let's look at the response to that request.

200
00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:34.000
Here we see God is pleased to grant what Moses has asked for.

201
00:15:34.000 --> 00:15:36.000
But he also reframes it slightly.

202
00:15:36.000 --> 00:15:38.000
Look now at verse 19.

203
00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:47.000
And he said, I will make all my, doesn't say glory, I will make all my goodness pass before you.

204
00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:51.000
And will proclaim before you my name.

205
00:15:51.000 --> 00:15:57.000
So God is going to show Moses more of his glory but he reframes that as goodness and his name.

206
00:15:57.000 --> 00:16:02.000
It's interesting when we think of glory, we don't automatically always think of goodness.

207
00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:05.000
We think of things that are big and grand.

208
00:16:05.000 --> 00:16:11.000
So it's interesting that the Lord uses the word goodness to describe his glory.

209
00:16:11.000 --> 00:16:13.000
We'll perhaps return to that in a moment.

210
00:16:13.000 --> 00:16:19.000
But God is revealing his glorious goodness in at least a couple of ways here.

211
00:16:19.000 --> 00:16:26.000
God is going to show Moses his glory but he's also going to speak to Moses about his glory.

212
00:16:26.000 --> 00:16:31.000
He says, I'm going to cause my goodness to pass before you and I'm going to proclaim my name.

213
00:16:31.000 --> 00:16:38.000
So imagine, I don't know, like seeing a beautiful sunset and you're looking out at the sky standing next to somebody

214
00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:43.000
and all you know to say is, wow, that's what's going through your mind, wow.

215
00:16:43.000 --> 00:16:47.000
And this person beside you, they're looking at that same sunset

216
00:16:47.000 --> 00:16:53.000
and they're thinking about exactly what is going on scientifically and they're in awe and wonder about that.

217
00:16:53.000 --> 00:16:58.000
And then all of a sudden they start thinking about the specific colors that are there in front of them

218
00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:02.000
and that leads to them crafting this beautiful poem in their mind

219
00:17:02.000 --> 00:17:04.000
with the perfect analogies about what they're seeing.

220
00:17:04.000 --> 00:17:06.000
Now both of you are seeing the same thing.

221
00:17:06.000 --> 00:17:10.000
But one of them is seeing a little more detail than what you're seeing.

222
00:17:10.000 --> 00:17:12.000
So you get a similar thing here.

223
00:17:12.000 --> 00:17:16.000
There's this kind of wow factor of like this is who God is.

224
00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:19.000
Moses is not left to interpret what he is seeing.

225
00:17:19.000 --> 00:17:25.000
Moses says, God says, here I am and this is who I am specifically.

226
00:17:25.000 --> 00:17:27.000
Okay, this is what's going on here.

227
00:17:27.000 --> 00:17:30.000
So he passes by Moses.

228
00:17:30.000 --> 00:17:33.000
Now it says nobody can look directly at God's being and live.

229
00:17:33.000 --> 00:17:39.000
So God puts him in the cleft of a rock and he covers him with his hand until he passes by

230
00:17:39.000 --> 00:17:42.000
and he allows him to see his back.

231
00:17:42.000 --> 00:17:47.000
Now this is mysterious, this kind of revelation of God, but nonetheless it is good.

232
00:17:47.000 --> 00:17:50.000
This is really happening here.

233
00:17:50.000 --> 00:17:52.000
But then so that's what Moses is seeing.

234
00:17:52.000 --> 00:17:54.000
That's that kind of wow.

235
00:17:54.000 --> 00:17:57.000
But then God proclaims his name.

236
00:17:57.000 --> 00:18:02.000
Now remember as we've seen already in Exodus, his name is the revelation of his nature.

237
00:18:02.000 --> 00:18:05.000
So the Lord emphatically repeats his name.

238
00:18:05.000 --> 00:18:08.000
This is the very name I am who I am.

239
00:18:08.000 --> 00:18:10.000
It says the Lord, the Lord.

240
00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:15.000
This is the name that he revealed to Moses earlier on in the book of Exodus.

241
00:18:15.000 --> 00:18:18.000
So this isn't just information that the Lord is imparting here.

242
00:18:18.000 --> 00:18:21.000
This isn't just like a theology course or something.

243
00:18:21.000 --> 00:18:27.000
This is his very identity that he's putting before Moses here and now it's through the word.

244
00:18:27.000 --> 00:18:30.000
Now this is a major moment in the Old Testament.

245
00:18:30.000 --> 00:18:33.000
Now of course this is a book about who God is.

246
00:18:33.000 --> 00:18:38.000
Here he gives this statement about his nature and it's going to be repeated throughout the Old Testament.

247
00:18:38.000 --> 00:18:40.000
You see it in places like Psalm 103.

248
00:18:40.000 --> 00:18:43.000
You see it in the book of Nehemiah, the book of Jonah.

249
00:18:43.000 --> 00:18:45.000
We could go on and list all these examples.

250
00:18:45.000 --> 00:18:50.000
This is a foundational statement, almost like a creed that says this is who our God is.

251
00:18:50.000 --> 00:18:52.000
This is who the Lord is.

252
00:18:52.000 --> 00:18:55.000
And that's then expounded even further in the New Testament.

253
00:18:55.000 --> 00:19:00.000
What God says about himself begins with what he says about his character.

254
00:19:01.000 --> 00:19:04.000
He says a God, when he proclaims his name, he says,

255
00:19:04.000 --> 00:19:08.000
the Lord the Lord, a God merciful and gracious,

256
00:19:08.000 --> 00:19:13.000
slow to anger and abounding in steadfast love and faithfulness.

257
00:19:13.000 --> 00:19:18.000
So what is the very first thing God wants us to know about who he is like?

258
00:19:18.000 --> 00:19:21.000
What is this statement front loaded with?

259
00:19:21.000 --> 00:19:24.000
The fact that he is merciful and gracious.

260
00:19:24.000 --> 00:19:26.000
He is merciful.

261
00:19:26.000 --> 00:19:30.000
This is telling us that his heart is full of compassion,

262
00:19:30.000 --> 00:19:34.000
especially for his children.

263
00:19:34.000 --> 00:19:36.000
He is gracious.

264
00:19:36.000 --> 00:19:41.000
He is freely, he's a God who freely and abundantly gives good gifts

265
00:19:41.000 --> 00:19:49.000
because this is who he is, it's the overflow of his gracious nature because he's a God of grace.

266
00:19:49.000 --> 00:19:51.000
He's slow to anger.

267
00:19:51.000 --> 00:19:53.000
This is speaking of God's patience.

268
00:19:53.000 --> 00:19:56.000
It's not to say that God is totally without anger.

269
00:19:56.000 --> 00:20:00.000
There's a thing called righteous anger, which is right to be angry at certain things.

270
00:20:00.000 --> 00:20:05.000
But God is slow to anger in that he doesn't have a short fuse.

271
00:20:05.000 --> 00:20:08.000
He's so patient with us.

272
00:20:08.000 --> 00:20:10.000
He is long suffering towards us.

273
00:20:10.000 --> 00:20:18.000
We saw that as the Lord provided water and food for his complaining people in the wilderness time and time again.

274
00:20:18.000 --> 00:20:21.000
You see this in the New Testament, 2 Peter 3.9.

275
00:20:21.000 --> 00:20:24.000
It says the Lord is not slow concerning his promise.

276
00:20:24.000 --> 00:20:29.000
Some people count slowness, but is long suffering to usward, not willing that any should perish,

277
00:20:29.000 --> 00:20:32.000
but that all should come to repentance.

278
00:20:32.000 --> 00:20:35.000
In other words, why has the Lord not returned?

279
00:20:35.000 --> 00:20:43.000
Because he is long suffering, waiting to bring all of those who will come to him in repentance to himself.

280
00:20:43.000 --> 00:20:47.000
And he's a God who is abounding in steadfast love and faithfulness.

281
00:20:47.000 --> 00:20:52.000
It's just speaking about God's covenant keeping love.

282
00:20:52.000 --> 00:20:59.000
His faithfulness is his rock solid commitment to his people and his promises.

283
00:20:59.000 --> 00:21:02.000
And it is boundless. It is immeasurable.

284
00:21:02.000 --> 00:21:05.000
That's his character.

285
00:21:05.000 --> 00:21:09.000
But he then goes to talk about his actions that flows from his character.

286
00:21:09.000 --> 00:21:13.000
That's what he says next. He says in verse 7, keeping steadfast love.

287
00:21:13.000 --> 00:21:15.000
This is Exodus 34, 7 by the way.

288
00:21:16.000 --> 00:21:22.000
Keeping steadfast love for thousands, forgiving iniquity and transgression and sin.

289
00:21:22.000 --> 00:21:26.000
Paul's there. So God keeps steadfast love.

290
00:21:26.000 --> 00:21:30.000
He guards it, he maintains it. For who? For thousands.

291
00:21:30.000 --> 00:21:32.000
That's not just a reference to thousands of people.

292
00:21:32.000 --> 00:21:38.000
If you go to Deuteronomy 7.9, it explicitly says it's for thousands of generations.

293
00:21:38.000 --> 00:21:42.000
So it's implied here, but it's specific there in Deuteronomy.

294
00:21:42.000 --> 00:21:44.000
That's what he's saying here.

295
00:21:44.000 --> 00:21:48.000
This isn't like a mathematical statement as though, like, I'm going to work with a thousand generations.

296
00:21:48.000 --> 00:21:51.000
In a thousand one, I'm done.

297
00:21:51.000 --> 00:21:55.000
It's not a kind of precise statement. It's a statement of abundance.

298
00:21:55.000 --> 00:21:57.000
It's speaking of the largeness of his love.

299
00:21:57.000 --> 00:22:03.000
It's like a flood sweeping through generations, flowing through the centuries,

300
00:22:03.000 --> 00:22:05.000
even to this present day.

301
00:22:05.000 --> 00:22:08.000
This is his love. That's the picture here.

302
00:22:08.000 --> 00:22:10.000
What does that love bring about?

303
00:22:10.000 --> 00:22:13.000
It brings about forgiveness.

304
00:22:13.000 --> 00:22:19.000
That literally means to carry the burden, like carry the burden of our sin.

305
00:22:19.000 --> 00:22:24.000
So if you back out this morning, and as I've done before, not here, but back out and hit a car,

306
00:22:24.000 --> 00:22:30.000
some, you're wondering about my driving now, somebody's going to pay for that.

307
00:22:30.000 --> 00:22:36.000
Like either the person who backed into the car or like, you're going to have to take that burden on yourself.

308
00:22:36.000 --> 00:22:42.000
So when God's saying, he forgives sin, sin still has to be dealt with.

309
00:22:42.000 --> 00:22:45.000
I overlook sin. I'm going to turn to by and die to sin.

310
00:22:45.000 --> 00:22:48.000
It's more that he carries the burden himself.

311
00:22:48.000 --> 00:22:51.000
He takes that burden on himself.

312
00:22:51.000 --> 00:22:57.000
And on the flip side here, we also see that God is not just loving and forgiving.

313
00:22:57.000 --> 00:23:03.000
He's also the God who will by no means clear the guilty,

314
00:23:03.000 --> 00:23:07.000
visiting the iniquities of the fathers on the children

315
00:23:07.000 --> 00:23:13.000
and the children's children to the third and fourth generation.

316
00:23:13.000 --> 00:23:21.000
So to speak of God's mercy and grace and love in such glowing terms is not to say that he's soft.

317
00:23:21.000 --> 00:23:27.000
He takes sin seriously. He's a God who does punish the guilty.

318
00:23:27.000 --> 00:23:34.000
This is why I'm, the pastor Mark Devere refers to this passage as the great riddle of the Old Testament.

319
00:23:34.000 --> 00:23:36.000
It really is a great paradox.

320
00:23:36.000 --> 00:23:41.000
It's like how can God be both just and loving at the same time?

321
00:23:41.000 --> 00:23:43.000
We'll return to that in a moment.

322
00:23:43.000 --> 00:23:47.000
But to add to the tension of his justice and his love,

323
00:23:47.000 --> 00:23:53.000
you then had this part about him visiting the sins of the fathers on the children to the third and fourth generation.

324
00:23:53.000 --> 00:23:57.000
Happy Mother's Day.

325
00:23:57.000 --> 00:24:02.000
What a verse to get to Child Dedication Sunday.

326
00:24:02.000 --> 00:24:13.000
Sadly, it is true and tragic that sinful patterns and consequences that go with those patterns often do continue on from generation to generation.

327
00:24:13.000 --> 00:24:18.000
I don't have to convince you of that. We see it.

328
00:24:18.000 --> 00:24:28.000
That's one of the reasons why we included not just children, but parents in this time of dedication this morning in the church as well.

329
00:24:28.000 --> 00:24:32.000
As we look to the Lord together in this.

330
00:24:32.000 --> 00:24:37.000
But you know there's a great comfort in what he says here too.

331
00:24:37.000 --> 00:24:40.000
Where's that comfort found in?

332
00:24:40.000 --> 00:24:43.000
It's kind of found in the numbers once again.

333
00:24:43.000 --> 00:24:47.000
So God deals with sin, it says, to the third and the fourth generation.

334
00:24:47.000 --> 00:24:52.000
But don't forget the number that's coming up behind that third and fourth.

335
00:24:52.000 --> 00:24:53.000
What was it?

336
00:24:53.000 --> 00:24:55.000
It was the number a thousand.

337
00:24:55.000 --> 00:24:58.000
He shows his love to the thousandth generation.

338
00:24:58.000 --> 00:25:00.000
So do you see the difference? You see what's going on here?

339
00:25:00.000 --> 00:25:04.000
So yes, the consequences of sin are real and devastating.

340
00:25:04.000 --> 00:25:11.000
But the love of God and the powerful work that he accomplishes through it is far greater.

341
00:25:11.000 --> 00:25:15.000
God's people might have run from him in their idolatry.

342
00:25:15.000 --> 00:25:17.000
And it was wrong, of course it was.

343
00:25:17.000 --> 00:25:21.000
But a tidal wave of mercy is heading their way.

344
00:25:21.000 --> 00:25:24.000
We already see the evidence even of this here.

345
00:25:24.000 --> 00:25:30.000
We want to look into all of it, but here we have God renewing the covenant and restoring his relationship with his people.

346
00:25:30.000 --> 00:25:33.000
You see this in Isaiah 54, verses seven and eight.

347
00:25:33.000 --> 00:25:34.000
God says this.

348
00:25:34.000 --> 00:25:40.000
He says, for a brief moment I deserted you, but with great compassion I will gather you.

349
00:25:40.000 --> 00:25:45.000
In overflowing anger for a moment I hid my face from you.

350
00:25:45.000 --> 00:25:49.000
But with everlasting love I will have compassion on you.

351
00:25:49.000 --> 00:25:51.000
The goodness of God.

352
00:25:51.000 --> 00:25:56.000
The glory revealed here, yes, is like a tidal wave flowing through generations,

353
00:25:56.000 --> 00:25:59.000
even sweeping through the whole world,

354
00:25:59.000 --> 00:26:04.000
gathering a people for the glory of his name from every tribe, tongue and nation.

355
00:26:04.000 --> 00:26:09.000
Yes, sin abounds, but grace does much more abound.

356
00:26:09.000 --> 00:26:16.000
You know, to apply this personally, yes, your sin and mine is serious and deserving of judgment,

357
00:26:16.000 --> 00:26:19.000
but it is no match for God's grace.

358
00:26:19.000 --> 00:26:26.000
God can break through your life in a way that impacts you, bringing you to himself,

359
00:26:26.000 --> 00:26:31.000
that impacts your family, and even impacts generations to come.

360
00:26:31.000 --> 00:26:35.000
This is the glory that is being revealed here.

361
00:26:35.000 --> 00:26:41.000
But the final thing I want to say is this is the glory that is being revealed in Jesus.

362
00:26:41.000 --> 00:26:47.000
When Jesus' disciples reflected on their time with Jesus, I think Caleb mentioned this last week.

363
00:26:47.000 --> 00:26:50.000
They said this, John 1.14,

364
00:26:50.000 --> 00:27:02.000
we beheld his glory, the glory as of the only begotten of the Father, full of grace and truth.

365
00:27:02.000 --> 00:27:09.000
Jesus himself says in John 17.6 that he revealed God's name.

366
00:27:09.000 --> 00:27:15.000
Do you want to see God's name proclaimed? His nature put before us, it's in the person of Jesus.

367
00:27:15.000 --> 00:27:23.000
The author of Hebrews, Hebrews 1.3 says that Jesus is the radiance of the glory of God

368
00:27:23.000 --> 00:27:27.000
and the exact representation of his being.

369
00:27:27.000 --> 00:27:35.000
So God's glory, the radiance of his splendor, the beauty of his being is seen in the person of his son.

370
00:27:35.000 --> 00:27:43.000
All of God's perfections dwell in Jesus, the eternal Son of God.

371
00:27:43.000 --> 00:27:56.000
On Mount Sinai, Moses caught a glimpse of God's glory, but you and I are invited to gaze upon his glory in the face of Jesus Christ.

372
00:27:56.000 --> 00:28:05.000
We can see God's glory by the power of the Spirit when we fix our eyes by faith on Jesus Christ.

373
00:28:05.000 --> 00:28:11.000
Because it's in Jesus Christ that the answer of that riddle of the Old Testament is found.

374
00:28:11.000 --> 00:28:20.000
So how can God be merciful and just? Because Jesus, the very embodiment of his glory,

375
00:28:20.000 --> 00:28:27.000
took our sin upon himself, took our guilt upon himself and died in our place.

376
00:28:27.000 --> 00:28:33.000
How can God forgive sin? So he takes that burden on himself. What does he do with it? How does God pay for our sin?

377
00:28:33.000 --> 00:28:42.000
Because Jesus took that burden and he paid the cost when he died for us on Calvary.

378
00:28:42.000 --> 00:28:51.000
So where do we see God's glorious goodness, his mercy, his grace, his loving kindness shining most brightly?

379
00:28:51.000 --> 00:28:58.000
What is that? The cross. It is there that we see the mercy, grace and the love of God.

380
00:28:59.000 --> 00:29:08.000
See that he, in Jesus, was willing to lay aside heaven's glory to be clothed in flesh and died to make us his own.

381
00:29:08.000 --> 00:29:17.000
So yes, the greatest blessing in life is not God's gifts, those are the things that we might be desiring this morning.

382
00:29:17.000 --> 00:29:22.000
The greatest blessing is God himself and God has given himself to us.

383
00:29:22.000 --> 00:29:29.000
He's offering himself to us even today in the person of Jesus Christ.

384
00:29:29.000 --> 00:29:36.000
So when we pray, please show me your glory. He shows us Jesus.

385
00:29:36.000 --> 00:29:44.000
So how should we respond? We should join Moses in praying that we might see more of him.

386
00:29:44.000 --> 00:29:48.000
Let's be a people who do that. If you've never seen his glory, pray that you might see his glory.

387
00:29:48.000 --> 00:29:53.000
If you've seen his glory a hundred times, you know there's more to see. Keep seeking after him.

388
00:29:53.000 --> 00:30:00.000
And then gaze upon his glory in Jesus. You might see more and more of him.

389
00:30:00.000 --> 00:30:07.000
And then like Moses, chapter 34 and verse 8, fall before him in worship.

390
00:30:07.000 --> 00:30:17.000
See the more we see of God's goodness in Jesus, the more we adore him and the more we will gladly offer up our lives to him because he's worthy.

391
00:30:17.000 --> 00:30:23.000
He is good. He is glorious. Let's pray.

392
00:30:23.000 --> 00:30:32.000
Lord, I pray that you would open our eyes to see more of your glory in the face of Jesus Christ.

393
00:30:32.000 --> 00:30:45.000
Lord, so often we get distracted by so many other things as though they were ultimate, as though they were the thing that was going to satisfy the restlessness, hunger, the thirst of our souls.

394
00:30:45.000 --> 00:30:53.000
When all the while it is you and your glory, your glorious goodness that does that, what I pray that you turn our eyes to you.

395
00:30:53.000 --> 00:31:05.000
And Lord, we praise you that you are pleased to make yourself known to us. So we pray, Lord, show us more of your glory. Amen.

